Question:
According to the figure, which of the following statements about oriented links is correct?

Options:
A: Reversing the orientation of all components gives an equivalent oriented link
B: Reversing the orientation of only one component necessarily yields an equivalent link
C: Every link has exactly one orientation
D: Oriented link diagrams are in one-to-one correspondence with oriented links in \(S^3\)
E: \\

message.content:
Reversing the orientation of all components of an oriented link yields an equivalent oriented link (there is an orientation-preserving homeomorphism of \(S^3\) carrying the link to itself with all component orientations reversed). So A is correct.

Reversing only one component need not give an equivalent oriented link (e.g., Hopf link with linking number sign change), so B is false.

A link with \(n\) components has \(2^n\) possible orientations, so C is false.

Oriented link diagrams are not in 1-1 correspondence with oriented links in \(S^3\) because different diagrams can represent the same oriented link up to Reidemeister moves, so D is false.

E is empty.

Answer:A
